"about 1220":"omkring 1220","1309":"1309","1270":"1270","1170":"1170","about 1230":"omkring 1230","Wales":"Wales","Carmarthenshire, Wales":"Carmarthenshire, Wales"},"nl":{"about 1220–after 1250":"circa 1220–na 1250","1202–1270":"1202–1270","1220–1250":"1220–1250","1220–Female":"1220–Overleden","1230–1309":"1230–1309","1185–Male":"1185–Overleden","1170–Female":"1170–Overleden","1202":"1202","after 1250":"na 1250","1220":"1220","1230":"1230","1185":"1185","1250":"1250","about 1220":"circa 1220","1309":"1309","1270":"1270","1170":"1170","about 1230":"circa 1230","Wales":"Wales","Carmarthenshire, Wales":"Carmarthenshire, Wales"},"en":{"about 1220–after 1250":"about 1220–after 1250","1202–1270":"1202–1270","1220–1250":"1220–1250","1220–Female":"1220–Deceased","1230–1309":"1230–1309","1185–Male":"1185–Deceased","1170–Female":"1170–Deceased","1202":"1202","after 1250":"after 1250","1220":"1220","1230":"1230","1185":"1185","1250":"1250","about 1220":"about 1220","1309":"1309","1270":"1270","1170":"1170","about 1230":"about 1230","Wales":"Wales","Carmarthenshire, Wales":"Carmarthenshire, Wales","nameMeanings":[{"name":"ap","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Dutch: occupational name for a cobbler.","Slovenian: nickname for a talkative person, from <i>lapati</i> ‘to babble’, or a topographic name from dialect <i>lap</i> ‘abyss’. Compare   Lapp   4."],"variants":[{"name":"Lapp","meanings":["German, English, and Dutch: from Middle High German and Middle English <i>lappe</i>, Middle Dutch <i>lap</i> ‘cloth, patch, rag’, a metonymic occupational name for a mender of clothes or shoes, or a nickname given to someone who wore ragged clothes or garments with loose folds, flaps, or hanging sleeves, or who had fleshy folds of skin on his face, neck, or body.","German: nickname for a simple-minded person, from Middle Low German <i>lappe</i> ‘fool’. This surname (in any of the two possible senses; see also 1 above) is also found in France (mainly Alsace, also Lorraine).","English: nickname from Anglo-Norman French <i>lappe</i> ‘burdock’, perhaps for someone with a prickly character."]}]},{"name":"Cadwgan","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["Welsh:  see  Cadogan  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Cadogan","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Dermot.","Welsh (Pembrokeshire and Glamorgan) and Irish (of Welsh origin): from the Old Welsh personal name <i>Catgucaun</i>, <i>Catguocawn</i>, modernized as <i>Cadwgon</i>. It is composed of <i>cad</i> ‘battle’ + <i>gogawn</i> ‘honour, glory’. See also   Wogan  . The surname is stressed, like its Welsh original, on the penultimate syllable, hence its occasional development to   Duggan  .","Irish: from <b>Ó Ceadagáin</b> ‘descendant of <i>Ceadagán</i>’."]}]},{"name":"Madog","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Traditional name, possibly having the sense ‘fortunate’ or alternatively from Celtic <i>aodh</i> ‘fire’."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Foel","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Biblical name, composed of two different Hebrew elements, <i>Yah(weh)</i> and <i>El</i>, both of which mean ‘God’ the implication of the name is that the Hebrew God, <i>Yahweh</i>, is the only true god. This is a common name in the Bible, being borne by, among others, one of King David's ‘mighty men’ (1 Chronicles 11:38), and a minor prophet who lived in the 8th century  bc . The name has been perennially popular as a Jewish name; it was also taken up by the Puritans and other Christian fundamentalists. The name has long been in regular use in North America but was uncommon in Britain until the 1990s. Well-known bearers of the name include the American singer and entertainer  Joel Grey  (  b. 1932 ), the West Indian cricketer  Joel Garner  (  b. 1952 ), and the American film director  Joel Coen  (  b. 1954 ). The French form  <b>Joël</b>  is also used in the English-speaking world."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Madog Foel ap Cadwgan was born about 1220, in Wales, his father, Cadwgon ap Iorwerth, was 37 and his mother, Gwenllian  ferch Hywel, was 52. He had at least 1 son with Lleucu ferch Gruffudd. He died after 1250."},"et":{"about 1220–after 1250":"umbes 1220–pärast 1250","1202–1270":"1202–1270","1220–1250":"1220–1250","1220–Female":"1220–Surnud","1230–1309":"1230–1309","1185–Male":"1185–Surnud","1170–Female":"1170–Surnud","1202":"1202","after 1250":"pärast 1250","1220":"1220","1230":"1230","1185":"1185","1250":"1250","about 1220":"umbes 1220","1309":"1309","1270":"1270","1170":"1170","about 1230":"umbes 1230","Wales":"Wales","Carmarthenshire, Wales":"Carmarthenshire, Wales"},"fi":{"about 1220–after 1250":"noin 1220–1250 jälkeen","1202–1270":"1202–1270","1220–1250":"1220–1250","1220–Female":"1220–Kuollut","1230–1309":"1230–1309","1185–Male":"1185–Kuollut","1170–Female":"1170–Kuollut","1202":"1202","after 1250":"1250 jälkeen","1220":"1220","1230":"1230","1185":"1185","1250":"1250","about 1220":"noin 1220","1309":"1309","1270":"1270","1170":"1170","about 1230":"noin 1230","Wales":"Wales","Carmarthenshire, Wales":"Carmarthenshire, Wales"},"fr":{"about 1220–after 1250":"environ 1220–après 1250","1202–1270":"1202–1270","1220–1250":"1220–1250","1220–Female":"1220–Décédée","1230–1309":"1230–1309","1185–Male":"1185–Décédé","1170–Female":"1170–Décédée","1202":"1202","after 1250":"après 1250","1220":"1220","1230":"1230","1185":"1185","1250":"1250","about 1220":"environ 1220","1309":"1309","1270":"1270","1170":"1170","about 1230":"environ 1230","Wales":"Galles","Carmarthenshire, Wales":"Carmarthenshire, Galles","lifeSummary":"Lorsque Madog Foel ap Cadwgan est né environ 1220, à Galles, son père, Cadwgon ap Iorwerth, avait 37 ans et sa mère, Gwenllian  ferch H